Here you make the mistake that other economists make of confusing current
GDP for economic efficiency.  Fortunately, responsible economists don't
make this mistake.

Let's look at some of these examples.  Walking vs. driving, for example.
For economists, if people want to drive then they're better off when
they're able to drive.  Now let's suppose that you're trying to choose
between walking or driving when you can afford both.  Well, if you choose
to drive, you consume more.  This increases current GDP through
consumption: it increases demand for cars slightly, increasing the standard
of living for those who make cars, etc.

But what happens when you choose to save your money and walk?  Do you just
bury that wealth in a hole where it never comes out again?  Obviously not.
If you have the money, you will either save it so you can consume something
else (maybe you're saving up for a new air conditioner instead! ;) ) or you
will simply save it in the bank, where it will earn interest.  This is not
an economic bad, because when the bank's got it, the bank will INVEST it,
and investment leads to economic growth through the creation of new
capital.  An economy which one day decided it would completely cease
investing and just spend all of its money today would have an amazing GDP
this quarter, but would find themselves in the deepest poverty in the
coming years, as machinery broke down, homelessness occurred, demand
slumped, etc.

In other words, walking instead of biking doesn't hurt the economy one bit,
because you're USING that money to consume something else or paying someone
else (in this case, the bank,) to invest it.  Either way it's an economic
good for neoclassical economists.

Anyway, I presume that this was meant to answer my question as to how
spending money on prisons makes money for the government.  Of course, it
doesn't.  Government spending today has a crowding out effect, causing
investment to decrease.  And though government spending does increase GDP
and thus tax revenues, it does not pay for itself, nor do neoclassical
economists believe that it does.  Reagan thought that it would; he was
obviously wrong.

